        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>244 West 52.<lb/>
                2. 11. 50<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S. Morais<lb/>
                Rev and Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Many thanks for your<lb/> reply&#59; the work of Luzzato about<lb/> the Falasha&#39;s was not for me&#44; but for a<lb/> lady&#44; a member of my congregation and<lb/> a member of our Literary Circle.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have lent her your paper on the<lb/> subject &#40;in Penn monthly&#41;&#44; Stern&#39;s<lb/> travels in Abyssinia&#44; which I picked<lb/> up in London&#44; and the vol. of the London Society<lb/> for Heb. Literature containing Halevy&#39;s<lb/> travels &#40;or an epitome&#41;.<lb/></p>
            <p>I believe the lady is known to you&#45;&#45;<lb/> a Miss Salamon&#44; sister of the late<lb/> Mrs Alma Hendricks.<lb/></p>
            <p>I do not therefore like to ask you to lend<lb/> your copy&#44; especially as the matter<lb/> is not&#44; I presume&#44; of great moment.<lb/>  With regard to the elder Luzzato&#39;s<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>books&#44; I know his trans. of the Penta<lb/>teuch etc&#44; having seen it in M&#39;chester<lb/> &#40;Eng&#41; where many of my old<lb/> congregants are Italian &#40;in language&#41;.<lb/>  But it must be an expensive work com&#45;<lb/>plete&#59; if it is moderate in cost&#44; I would<lb/> ask you to obtain it for me&#59; I would<lb/> much like to know more of his works&#44;&#45;&#45;if<lb/> they are in French or Italian it would<lb/> make little difference&#44; as I am familiar<lb/> with the first and three years ago was<lb/> able to understand the latter very fairly.<lb/>  My father&#44; I am rejoiced to say&#44; is<lb/> much better and I hope by this<lb/> time is in full work again.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping you and yr family are<lb/> well I am<lb/> Reverend dear sir<lb/> vry try<lb/> H P Mendes.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
